The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT28 NT11  
   NT11 has no binary productions, so it always produces exactly one terminal.  
   Hence NT28 would have to generate 14 terminals and NT11 the last (15-th) one.  
   The last symbol of the given string is t6, but NT11 can never produce t6.  
   Therefore this branch is impossible.

2. S → NT2 NT32  
   NT32 has no binary productions either, so it produces exactly one terminal – the
   very last one in the string.  NT32 can generate t6, so the last symbol t6 fits
   and we must let NT32 produce it.  
   Consequently NT2 must generate the first 14 terminals.

   NT2 has exactly one binary rule: NT2 → NT0 NT29  
   (all its other rules are single–terminal productions).  
   Therefore:
   • NT0 produces the first terminal of the 14-symbol prefix,  
     leaving 13 symbols for NT29.  
   • NT29 has only one binary rule: NT29 → NT19 NT6 (otherwise it is
     single-terminal).  Thus in every 13-symbol string produced by NT29,
     the last symbol must come from NT6.

   So the 14-symbol prefix must look like  
     (token from NT0) … (token from NT19) (token from NT6)

   In the given string that prefix is  
     t1 t15 t6 t2 t16 t4 t8 t0 t20 t2 t15 t10 t16 t18  
     and the last symbol of this prefix is t18.

   But NT6 can generate
     t0, t1, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9, t10, t12, t16  
     (either directly or as the first of two terminals in NT6 → NT20 NT32,
      with the second one restricted to t5, t6, t10, t11, t13, t17).  
   t18 is not among these possibilities, so NT6 can never finish a string with t18.

   Hence NT29 cannot generate the required 13-symbol suffix, and NT2 cannot
   generate the 14-symbol prefix.

Since neither of the two possible expansions of S can yield the given 15-terminal
string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT28 NT11  
2. S → NT2 NT32  

In either case, the very first terminal symbol of any derived string must come from the left-hand non-terminal of the chosen production (NT28 or NT2, respectively).

• NT28  
  – Either produces a single terminal (t2, t18, t7, t13, t3, t16) or expands via NT28 → NT16 NT14, in which the first terminal must come from NT16.  
  – NT16’s only terminal productions are t17, t4, t15, t8, t14, t3, t5, t1, t2, t9, t13, t16.  
  – None of these is t20.  
  ⇒ A string derived from NT28 can never start with t20.

• NT2  
  – Either produces one of its own terminals (t9, t4, t2, t10, t15, t7, t13, t17, t18, t19, t14, t16, t0, …) or expands via NT2 → NT0 NT29, where the first terminal must come from NT0.  
  – NT0’s terminals are t1, t4, t18, t16, t3, t13, t0, t14, t7.  
  – Again, none of these is t20.  
  ⇒ A string derived from NT2 can never start with t20.

Therefore, no string generated by S can begin with the terminal t20.  
The given string begins with t20, so it cannot be produced by this grammar.
